{"title":"LooGLE: Can Long-Context Language Models Understand Long Contexts?","domain":"LLM_NLP","seeds":[{"problem":"Existing long-context LLM benchmarks are limited by relatively short documents, potential data leakage from outdated sources, and tasks that mostly test short-range dependencies rather than true long-range reasoning across a document.","method":"Introduce LooGLE, a long-context, generic evaluation benchmark built from post-2022 documents across arXiv papers, Wikipedia, and movie/TV scripts. It includes 776 extra-long documents (avg. ~19.3k words; many >100k words), 6,448 test instances, and 1,101 manually crafted, cross-validated long-dependency QA pairs spanning four challenging types (multiple information retrieval, timeline reorder, computation, and comprehension/reasoning), plus short-dependency QA, cloze, and summarization. The dataset construction, prompts, and evaluation code are open-sourced to enable reproducibility and periodic updates."},{"problem":"Timeline reordering in long texts is hard to evaluate reliably due to heterogeneous answer formats and a lack of robust sequence-similarity metrics.","method":"Standardize timeline-reorder outputs and propose four numeric-sequence deviation metrics—LSD (location square deviation), LMD (location mean deviation), SD (swap deviation), and SDD (swap distance deviation). Answers are normalized (e.g., Roman numerals), non-standard outputs are identified, and metrics are computed on standardized outputs to robustly score temporal ordering quality; implementations and usage are provided in the benchmark toolkit."},{"problem":"It is unclear which interventions (larger context windows, retrieval augmentation, and Chain-of-Thought prompting) actually improve long-context understanding in LLMs across realistic tasks.","method":"Conduct a comprehensive evaluation of eight LLMs (commercial and open-source) on LooGLE using automatic metrics and GPT-4-as-judge, while varying input length, adding retrieval via LlamaIndex, and applying zero-/few-shot CoT. Findings: commercial models outperform open-source; models do well on short QA/cloze/summarization but struggle on long-dependency QA; extending context length helps long-dependency QA but brings little gain for summarization; retrieval often degrades long-dependency QA for GPT-4/3.5; zero-shot CoT substantially boosts timeline reorder (~20% abs.) and computation (~10% abs.) but few-shot CoT can hurt these types."}]}
